3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Bitget calculates FET/USDT funding rates every 8 hours at 00:00, 08:00, and 16:00 UTC, based on the premium between perpetual and spot prices. The exchange uses a time-weighted average price methodology with a dampening factor to prevent manipulation. When funding rates are positive, long position holders pay shorts, and vice versa when negative. Bitget's funding rate calculation includes an interest rate component typically set at 0.01% per 8-hour period."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","FET","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"FET represents the AI narrative in crypto, making its funding rates highly sensitive to market sentiment around artificial intelligence developments. The token's mid-tier volume on Bitget creates opportunities for funding rate arbitrage while maintaining sufficient liquidity for position management. AI sector rotations often drive significant funding rate variations as traders position for narrative-driven price movements."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"FET/USDT funding rates on Bitget have exhibited strong correlation with broader AI sector momentum and Bitcoin market cycles. During AI narrative peaks, funding rates frequently exceeded 0.1% per 8-hour period as retail traders crowded into long positions. Conversely, during sector rotations away from AI tokens, funding rates often turned negative as leveraged longs were liquidated. The pair shows increased funding rate volatility during major AI announcements or regulatory developments affecting the sector. Weekend periods typically see reduced funding rate volatility due to lower trading volumes and institutional absence."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities and Strategy"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Optimal arbitrage windows for FET/USDT typically occur during high-volatility AI sector events when funding rates spike above 0.05% per 8-hour period. Bitget's copy trading ecosystem can amplify funding rate movements as followers mirror popular traders' positions, creating temporary imbalances. Cross-exchange arbitrage opportunities exist when Bitget's FET funding rates diverge significantly from other major exchanges due to localized demand. The 0.02% maker fee structure allows for profitable strategies when funding rates exceed 0.08% per period, accounting for transaction costs and slippage. Risk management requires monitoring AI sector news flow and maintaining hedged positions to capture funding payments while minimizing directional exposure."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations and Management"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"FET's AI sector classification exposes funding arbitrage strategies to narrative-driven volatility that can overwhelm funding payments through adverse price movements. Bitget's relatively newer exchange status means lower institutional presence, potentially leading to more pronounced retail-driven funding rate distortions. Liquidity constraints during market stress can result in wider spreads and slippage, eroding arbitrage profitability. The 8-hour funding interval creates overnight risk exposure, particularly during Asian trading hours when AI sector news often breaks. Effective risk management requires position sizing based on realized volatility and maintaining stop-losses to prevent funding gains from being erased by directional moves exceeding 2-3% during volatile periods."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How often are FET/USDT funding rates calculated on Bitget?","answer":"Bitget calculates FET/USDT funding rates every 8 hours at 00:00, 08:00, and 16:00 UTC. The rates are determined using a time-weighted average of the premium between the perpetual contract price and the underlying spot price over the preceding period."},{"question":"What makes FET funding rates different from other altcoins on Bitget?","answer":"FET funding rates are particularly sensitive to AI sector sentiment and narrative cycles, often showing higher volatility than general altcoins. The token's association with artificial intelligence creates funding rate spikes during AI-related news events and sector rotations."},{"question":"Can I profit from negative FET/USDT funding rates on Bitget?","answer":"Yes, when funding rates are negative, short position holders receive payments from long holders every 8 hours. This creates opportunities to earn funding payments while potentially benefiting from price declines during AI sector weakness."},{"question":"How do Bitget's FET/USDT funding rates compare to other exchanges?","answer":"Bitget's FET funding rates can diverge from other exchanges due to its strong retail presence and copy trading features, which can amplify positioning imbalances. These divergences create cross-exchange arbitrage opportunities for sophisticated traders."}]}]
